## Known Findings (do not duplicate)

- F-001: Zero-amount withdrawals can permanently disable emergency exits for an entire token (High, high)
- F-002: Emergency withdrawals let users recover principal while remaining counted in epoch accounting (High, high)
- F-003: Historical pool sizes are retroactively mutable for uninitialized epochs (Medium, medium)
- F-004: Arbitrary-token deposits credit the requested amount even when fewer or no tokens are received (High, high)
- F-005: Ignored Compound error codes can silently corrupt stablecoin state, brick future deposits, and expose principal to team sweeps (Medium, high)
- F-006: Skipped epochs and the hardcoded 2021 epoch start can brick dormant or never-before-used pools (Medium, high)
- F-007: Stablecoin stakers have no on-contract fallback exit if the Compound integration becomes unavailable (Medium, medium)
- F-008: Withdraw and emergency-withdraw can silently burn a user's claim when token transfers return false (Medium, high)
- F-010: Non-stable pool snapshots trust raw contract balances instead of tracked user stake (Medium, high)
- F-011: Permissionless interest sweeps can front-run stablecoin withdrawals and worsen liquidity shortfalls (Medium, low)
- F-012: Anyone can overwrite an already-initialized epoch-0 pool snapshot (Medium, high)
- F-013: Permissionless `getInterest()` can confiscate unrelated stablecoins held by the contract (Medium, high)
- F-014: Unexpected cToken transfers are misclassified as protocol yield and can be swept to the team (Medium, high)

